              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">Record number of executions in 2024
        </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.presidentialsummary.com/email/images/amnesty-international-global-executions-surge-2024-record-rise.png" alt="Amnesty International reports a record surge in global executions in 2024" href="https://www.presidentialsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Amnesty International reports a record surge in global executions in 2024. Credits: Amnesty International</i></p>
        </mj-text>
      
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-10-04-2025-h2-3-amnesty-international-reported?source=website" target="_blank">Amnesty International reported</a> a sharp 32% rise in global executions in 2024, with 1,518 recorded, which is the highest in nearly a decade. Iran, Iraq, and Saudi Arabia alone accounted for 91% of known executions. These three countries often use the death penalty as a means of silencing political dissent. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">In addition, 40% of these executions were based on drug crimes. China has a reputation for having the highest number of executions, but the figures remain unknown. There are also likely unrecorded instances from more secretive states like North Korea and Vietnam. Other countries that saw an increase were Egypt, Singapore, and Yemen.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Despite the dramatic rise in numbers, just 15 countries used this method of punishment. The US executed 25 people in 2024, making it the lone OECD country to practice the death penalty. Amnesty International added that 113 countries have entirely abolished the death penalty, and 145 have abolished it in law or practice. </p>
        </mj-text>
